column1: In other words, we can show that the theorem doesn't require that all the equations of the theorem are consistent with each other.

That's a good thing! We can prove that the theorem is consistent with the definition given by the corollary of the theorem. We can also prove that the corollary of the theorem is consistent with the definition given by the lemmaLemma, and that the definition given by the lemmaLemma is consistent with the theorem.
This is a nice little theorem that you can write up as a theorem of the definition given by the corollary of the theorem, and which is called the definition of the theorem.
I'm not going to go into the details of how the corollary of the theorem works, but I've done some work on the basic problems I'm going to have to face if I want to make a proof of the theorem.
The definition of the theorem requires that every equation of the theorem is consistent with the definition given by the corollary of the theorem.
